<Text>I had a good experience at this subway... with the food and cleanliness. Sometimes you go to a subway and usually you get the same quality. Sometime the quality is just not as good as other times. I had the chicken breast sandwich here on this visit, and was really good. I order this type of sandwich usually because its chicken breast and more healthy. Other subways sometimes leave the breast a little lacking... you can tell it was frozen or stored. Here, the chicken tasted and felt like a real chicken breast. Very good sandwich... and left me wanting another one. The restroom was also very clean. Smelled good and soapy. No trash anywhere. Looked like they keep sweeping/mopping regularly. The only reason I deducted one star is because of the wait. In my opinion, the workers could move a little faster. But, this is generally the case at any subway.<//Text>< Pictures>

All I wanted was a pizza on my birthday. Just a Chicago stuffed to the face with beer and court tv. They close at 9p on the weekdays. I called to place an order on a Monday at 8:30p. If you've been to Papa Murphy's, you know that's more than enough notice for 1 pizza. First girl answered the phone sounded like she was 13 and immediately stated they were not serving pizzas after she stated the store name. I was frustrated from a previous pizza incident that occurred about 30mins prior to this one so I hung up in frustration. Called back and got Nick and asked what time they closed. Politely he stated 9 BUT they are not serving anymore pizzas tonight. I asked why since they do not close until 9 and he stated it was because they were really busy that day. Uummmm no no no. I confronted him on it and asked the managers name and he gave me his and Harmons name without incident. < userid>

<user_name>Daz Wilkin<//user_name><date>1556512673244<//date>< rating>
5<//rating>
<Review>A small but interesting oasis in Eureka. Dog-friendly. Strolled around a few times with my dog for our afternoon walk, enjoying the sunny afternoon. Some interesting engines, trains and other miscellany explaining Eureka's logging history. There are also some buildings from when the area was a US Army fort. Definitely worth a visit.</Review>< Pics>

< Name>
Brokk Leavitt<//Name>
<Date>1578888107957< /Date>< resp>
None<//resp>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
Great place for a mellow, informative walk. There are several large steam powered logging machines, as well as 2 steam engines that are sure to interest just about anyone. The paths are well kept and lined with historical information signs about logging, the fort that once stood here, some events in local history, and Native American history. There is also a nice overlook towards the Mall and the ocean, which we saw a pretty sunset from.

The bathroom near the parking lot was clean and proper.

This park also hosts 6 stops and 3 gyms in the game Pokemon Go, making it a great spot to stay and play.< /review>

< text>
Eureka, Calif.
Free museum.

This Fort more like a lumber museum focusing on the town's tycoon.

Aside from the buildings and some barracks i wish more was focused on the fort, strategic location and challenges to live rather than for commerce.

The lumber history lesson was ok too though. Has many outdoor equipment. Heck, the museum is outdoor.

There is a Small, puny indoor exhibit i a nearby cabin.

This is the best touristy dork related stuff to do here in eureka.< /text>

<gmap_id>0x54d4000ec5e3a9d3:0x2ea794c195964b7</gmap_id>< review>
The view was great and the objects of interest around were entertaining to read. The plus side- is that there are a ton of Pokestops and Gyms for Pokemon Go.
The downside is that car access to their parking lot is closed later in the evening, as well as there being a constant mosquito problem from nearby stagnant water.
If you don't mind getting bit, or have insect repellent, it's a wonderful and free way to spend an hour even without Pokemon Go.</review>

<GmapID>0x54d4000ec5e3a9d3:0x2ea794c195964b7<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>
<response>None</response>< name>
Caryn Richards</name>
< rating>
2</rating>
< Pics>
None</Pics>
< text>
We were looking forward to visiting Fort Humboldt because we are Civil War re-enactors representing the 4th U.S. Regulars and we knew that U.S. Grant had been stationed there. The fort grounds were accessible, and there were a couple of buildings, but everything including the museum was closed when we came in the middle of the day. We saw that there were signboards, so we thought we would take a walking tour by ourselves.

The first signboard we came to had a photo of a guy who was wearing what would not pass for a Federal uniform by even the sloppiest historian, his musket held in his right hand somewhere between Shoulder Arms and Support Arms, a sword in his left hand (reasons unclear), modern shoes on his feet, and a sneer on his face. The sneer was because, (as we gathered from the sign board), he loosely represented the California Volunteer Militia left at the fort after the Federal troops left to fight the Civil War, and therefore his agenda was the state's (California State, we presume) policy of "Indian removal and extermination".

Interesting.

Other signboards pictured a woman, (in a tee-shirt but wearing a shawl and a Little House on the Prairie sunbonnet), variously representing a laundress and Harriet Simpson, and the California State Militia (still with the California State goal of exterminating Indians in mind), gathered for muster -- we assume -- wearing a variety of costumes including one that looked uncannily like a Confederate uniform.

Finding people in historically inaccurate costumes to photograph MAY be excusable for a museum, (I don't say it IS excusable, I merely say that we don't know what was up the day the signboards were designed -- maybe the people responsible for checking facts were down with the flu when the deadline for submitting photograph proofs came 'round), but the propaganda in the wording of the signs was heavy-handed indeed. A reading of the signboards gave us to understand that 1.) Harriet Simpson considered herself the only "lady" at the fort. 2.) The town directly beneath the fort used to be called Bucksport. This was because in 1849 when the Greg party got there, after being feted and feasted by the local population, an ungrateful guy named Buck carved his name on a tree, thereby claiming the town as his own.  3.) By 1860 Bucksport was a boom town with a large transient population, including Scandinavians, Irish, people from New Zealand and Australia, African Americans, and Chinese. 4.) In February of the same year, a group of "white vigilantes" murdered hundreds of Indian women and children in their sleep. 5.) When the U.S troops left the fort to fight the Civil War, they left the California  militia in charge. Some Indians came to the fort for protection. Not having the facilities to protect them, the officer in charge "build a corral". Somehow, according to the signboard, this led to the California soldiers [raping and beating] the Indians.(The brackets were the devise of the signboard). 6.) The Federal soldiers at the Fort drank too much.

One appreciates that the writers of the signboards had a point they wanted to drive home, but it was all a bit too heavy handed. The attention to historical detail was so poor at the first signboard that we didn't anticipate much attention to accuracy, anyway, but it would have been nice. Balance would have been appreciated, too.

Not at all recommended for anyone interested in Fort Humboldt itself, but the logging half of the park was very nicely done.< /text>

<Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
I visited Sixth and E Neighborhood Eatery with my mother and we both enjoyed it. The interior is hip, modern and impeccably clean. I ordered the veggie burger with feta and creamy house dressing instead of mayo and a side of onion rings. She ordered the mushroom Swiss burger also with a side of onion rings. The feta was forgotten on my burger, which was not a big deal and the waitress was very apologetic and got me a container of feta. I enjoyed the food overall, but I found the veggie patty itself to be bland and the burger needing more salt and sauce. Additionally, containers are too small to hold enough dipping sauce for all the onion rings. The staff was very friendly and I enjoyed the experience so I'd love to return, especially on a 1/2 price burger Tuesday.<//Review>

< Review>
On Tuesday's, with the purchase of a drink, burgers are half off. That being said, the full price burgers are worth it!! I have yet to be unsatisfied. The different varieties of fries are all so good. But this isn't just a burger joint. They have salads, pasta, fish and chips. Enjoy some local brews or cider on tap while soaking in the hip atmosphere. Just be warned, if you get the garlic fries, be prepared for lingering garlic breath, which is totally worth it in my opinion!< /Review>

< review>
Decent food but don't go in a party on a Tuesday unless everyone comes together as they won't seat you until all people have arrived.  After a long wait our party of five was seated at a table with bar stools with no place for purses or coats.  To get the special you have to order a beverage, I don't drink soda so I had to pay full price or soda price for water. One of our party ordered a beer was told there was a temporary problem and no beer, less than five minutes later two beers were served to the table behind us. Overall negative first impression.</review>

< Review>
The food here was fantastic and the portions are huge. Neither one of us ordered the burgers, which they are known for, and instead ordered the shrimp and pesto linguine and the fish tacos - both of which were delicious. We also ordered the deep fried pickles to start and that was the best decision weve ever made together. The housemade root beer was also great. Cant wait to try the burgers next time.

As a side note - Tuesdays are their half-price burger day, so I think it's a safe bet to assume that night would be busy and I think it's fair to expect things to take longer or be somewhat chaotic - it's the price you pay for you burger deals and I hardly think that's something you can hold against the restaurant or the staff. We went on a Wednesday and the place was nice and cozy, and the staff were super. It's definitely the best restaurant in eureka in my opinion.<//Review>

The establishment has a decent and cozy atmosphere. We understood that this place is a newer restaurant and very modern for this small city. I try to not to judge a place too much by just the food, but also thei small detials. To me the practice of outstanding  hygiene and their well-kept restrooms are as equally important. You can definitely perceive a very slight greasy scent when you first walk in. The employees were very helpful and polite. The service was efficient and in a timely manner.
Being a strict pescatarian I was very disappointed at the fish and chips. The fish was soggy and the taste was very blend. The tartar sauce was awful and it tasted too much of horseradish. The coleslaw wasn‚Äôt cold either and was completely flavorless. The chips were also extremely salty  :(
Too bad they don‚Äôt care too much to carry local fish either. I‚Äôd love to come back on our next trip and hopefully the fish & chips will be better and with more flavor. I hope they‚Äôll work a harder on improving or developing tastier recipes.
On a more positive note, my spouse loved his specialty sandwich with gravy, fries egg and fried chicken. Big boys would love this bad boy!! Check it out it is a cute modern spot with excellent beer selection. Happy dining everyone. Cheers! ‚úåÔ∏è</Text>

<Date>1612807186629< /Date><Rating>3<//Rating>< text>
Would have been 5 stars if I had gotten my car back fine.  After leaving the dealership Vanessa who had helped me was great!  I had paid Almost $900 for everything.  I was ok with that since the car needed normal maintenance.

The following day I paid everything, and was told that was it!  I was good to go!  Once I got my car back, I noticed a noise that was never there before.  My car had 66K miles and never had an issue.  Also for 6 years and 66K miles later, I had taken my car to BMW of Sherman Oaks.  No issues.  Now I have an issue after coming here for the first time ever.  And no one told me I had an issue until hours later Vanessa left a voice mail saying she forgot to tell me the mechanic found a problem with the E-Brake Clip and it would now cost $1,000 dollars to fix but I would get 10% off so $900.  After just coughing up $850+ I wasn't in the best mood.

I spoke with Henry the Director outside and explained to him that I truly feel Im being robbed right now.   Henry said the issue was very common between 40K and 60K on their cars.  I told him it doesn't mean it has to happen to mine because my car was fine when I dropped it off and NOW "SUDDENLY" I have this problem when I didn't have that issue before when I dropped it off.  Also BMW of Sherman Oaks never said anything or to be aware of it when I had taken it there last time.  I felt the mechanic knew this was a common issue and knowing that I just dropped over $850+ then I can Offord another $1000.  Its possible the mechanic did this on purpose?  I dont know.  I told him I know how mechanics work and get paid as I have family in the business and they have informed me of the scams and things they would do to customers so they could get paid more.  Henry understood my concern and was helpful and kind enough to reduce it to half as he said he would pay the other half.  All in all I paid roughly $1,250 and still wasnt happy.  I was told my car would be ready the following day as the process would only take 3 to 4 hours fixing a part that costs $20.00.  I got my car back 2 days later!! No calls to tell me what was going on or that they were working on the car still.   No apologies for the delay in getting my car back..

Overall not quite the experience I was hoping to have from BMW considering that the cars and parts are already expensive as we are driving great cars.  Not Hondas.    Wont be taking my car back there for service anymore.</text>

< review>
This was my first purchase at Valencia BMW and my experience was fantastic!! I first contacted them through Internet Sales and within ten minutes I received a call from Internet Sales Manager, Wesley Ramos. He then handled most of the sale by phone and email, from picking out the vehicle from their inventory online, my credit application and even my trade-in. When I arrived at the dealership Wesley was waiting for me and all I had to do was check out the vehicle, take it for a test drive and then right into finance wherein everything was all ready for me. From the time I arrived until I left with my new BMW it was just a little over one hour. Because of Wesley this had to be one of the best experiences I have had purchasing a new vehicle. It was also evident to me that Wesley cares very much about his clients and wants the best for them and clearly wants to build a long business relationship. Even after I purchased my new BMW and needed assistance, Wesley called me right  back and was again waiting for me at the dealership. I will defiantly purchase another vehicle from Wesley and will refer friends and family to him as well. I also want to give a shout out to Gary Kazandjian in Finance for a great job and no sales pressure, as well as Cole Schwartz in service for assisting with an update on the vehicles computer and answering all my questions. After my experience, Valencia BMW and Wesley have a customer for a very long time.</review>

I was coming from 60 miles away so I needed the car to have no issues. Picking it up was easy enough. On my drive home, I realized the cars steering wheel would need to be turned to the left to keep the car straight.  I figured they would fix any alignment issues when they said they would give me new tires and when they did that bmw inspection.  I, also, noticed during that drive home, the car would shake at a stop a little than I expected and heard a small crackling noise from the front driver side. I drove the car back immediately and the salesperson told me service was closed (it was Sunday) and to take the vehicle to my local BMW dealer for service. <Date>1542170718981</Date><Rate>1</Rate>< review>
Buyer Beware !  I strongly advise against buying a used vehicle from Valencia BMW.  After reading through other reviews, what happened to us seems like common practice.  We purchase a used vehicle a few days ago and had it inspected by a mechanic.  The mechanic found 2 oil leaks, worn brakes, and unmatched tires during the inspection.  All of these issues would lead to serious and expensive repairs if not addressed.

We purchased the vehicle at a fair, no haggle price from a dealer that sells the ultimate driving machines. But at a substantially higher price than from a private party.  A dealer that in my opinion was honest, reputable, and customer focused.  A dealer that conducted a 125 point vehicle inspection. Yet this vehicle was placed on the lot for sale.

We returned with the vehicle and informed them of the issues.  The service manager personally inspected the vehicle and after approximately an hour, he shared his results.  He found the oil leaks, gave us the worn measurements on the brakes and rotors, and agreed with us that the tires should be replaced.  We were told they would fix the oil leaks, but would not do anything about the brakes or tires.  Mind you, the oil leaks will be covered under warranty.  So, no skin off there back.  We returned the vehicle.

Adding insult to injury, at no time did we receive any customer service and/or did anyone try to keep us as satisfied customer.< /review>

I purchased my first electric vehicle from this dealer which was a 2013, Fiat 500e. I had a brand new 2013 Fiat a couple of years ago, which I really enjoyed but I just needed a larger car and traded it in for a Mini Cooper Countryman. I decided I wanted to save money so I purchased a second car to drive back and forth to work. When I walked into the dealership is greeted by Sergik who is contacting me by email answering all my questions promptly. He introduced me to a Salesman to show me the vehicle. The salesman was very knowledgeable answered all my questions the car was clean just like in the photo. It was late in the evening and I wasn't expecting to take a test drive because they were getting ready to close and I just wanted to look at the car real quick is very excited about it. I was going to come back the next day but they were not worried about the time and encouraged me to take a test drive if I wanted to do it then. The test drive went well and I came back the next day and purchase the vehicle. The vehicle was fully charged and clean. It was New Year's Eve so the dealership was very busy with several customers, but the atmosphere was so enjoyable I wasn't in a rush to leave they had appetizers food even a band because it was New Year's Eve day. All the sales people were nice and friendly. I can't say enough about how great this dealership was. I would recommend it to anyone that wants a BMW or any used vehicle for that matter. <Rate>1< /Rate><review>My experience with BMW was underwhelming at best.  My 2018 X5 broke down 60 miles from Valencia. I had to get the SUV towed to the dealership. I contacted the dealership, because I knew that I would not arrive by the time the service department closed. My goal was to pick up a loaner because BMW emergency roadside said that the car needed extensive work.  The front desk person, was useless.  She could not get a service person to talk to me, she said I would have to deal with it in the morning. I explained that i live 45 miles from the dealership.  She said she could not help me.

I woke up the next morning to see that I had received no messages from the service department.  I left my keys overnight, it is a bit disconcerting that there was no acknowledgement that they had my car and were reviewing the car.  I had to leave a few messages until my service rep called me back.  He said that my car needed a new fuel pump (a bummer for a one year old car) and that i would have to leave it for a week. He said that I had to come back to the dealer in order to get a loaner.  And the kicker, I would have to pay for the uber.

Finally, my car was ready.  I called ahead (remember I had 45 miles to drive) and asked if my SUV would be ready to go.  The same front desk person as before, said she would.  And, of course it was not ready and it was dirty.  They had to wash it, which took another 20 minutes.

I am leaving out having to call multiple times for updates etc... I will say that my car is now running. That is important.

In summary, you should have a game plan for cars delivered after service hours. You can coordinate with sales to have a loaner available.  Or, be willing to cover the cost of an uber ride back to the dealership.  If someone leaves a car overnight, have the assigned service person call or text first thing in the morning.    Finally, if someone asks for your car to be ready when you get there, then act accordingly.

BMW emergency roadside was not helpful either. They would only tow me to Valencia, they would not tow me to Santa Monica. They said i could pay what would equal $250.00.  At the time I assumed Valencia would allow me to rent a car locally.  I did not expect to have to drive bck there.

Overall, the repairman did his job, the rest did not.< /review><Pics>None<//Pics>< Response>

< Text>
Don't be fooled you can get the same deal on any BMW no matter where you go. Every dealer in the country will match any offer and in most cases do a dealer swap for the same exact car you're looking at. What makes a "good" dealership is how they treat you after they take your money. That's where Valencia BMW is terrible and why - in their own words- you should go somewhere else.

When leased my car, I was sold on how impressive the service dept at Valencia BMW you was. I was guaranteed flat bed pick up to my home or office wherever, a loaner car whatever I needed all I had to do was call and schedule the service.

I have been trying now for 3 weeks to schedule the regular service for my car and it's been a nightmare. When I originally called my car was approaching service, when I finally gave up it was  past due for service.  I have tried no less then 6 times to schedule pickup and drop off only to encounter excuse and obstacle after excuse and obstacle.  I have left messages for service managers not once to get a call back.  adding insult to injury the service staff here has ventured beyond rude to just poor taste, specifically a young lady named Jasmine, who I've had the distinct pleasure of speaking to at least 4 times, suggesting  "I can feel free to go somewhere else" if I was unsatisfied with their service department.

I was refereed to Valencia BMW by a family member who has bought multiple cars from the team here, I personally have sent 4 friends to the sales rep i worked with.  However, I finally took Jasmines advice and took my business somewhere else.

Yesterday I called Gil at Century West BMW He had me in and out in a few minutes and even dropped me off at my office.  I got my car back within a couple hours, while it was there they must have detailed it because it was SPOTLESS as if it where a brand new car.  Don't waste your time with Valencia BMW, all they care about is the sale and getting your money as soon as you sign paperwork all bets are off, you're on your own.<//Text>

I don't usually write reviews, but I was actually looking forward to writing this one. Valencia BMW is really outstanding. Seriously, these guys are absolutely great!  I am a 'car guy' through and through.  At any time I have 5 or 6 cars, everything from new BMWs to classic muscle cars.  I have bought and sold many cars, and dealt with many dealers.  Valencia BMW is the best experience I have had ever, and that is saying something.  I dealt with Martin Dino in sales, Hamid in finance, and both obviously enjoy what they do, and sincerely want their customers to be happy. Martin and I communicated by text and email over the course of 2 days, talked by phone several times, and at the end of the second day, Martin drove a beautiful new BMW to my house (to my house), so it would be there on my wife's birthday. He had all the paperwork with him and ready to go, we signed it at my dining room table in about 10 minutes, and that was it!  More importantly really, Valencia BMW obviously did everything they could to get the BMW I wanted, at a price and terms I could afford. No games, no highball/lowball nonsense, no tense conversations, no pressure. I actually live quite a ways away from Valencia, but I am going to call Valencia BMW first from now on.  Cars are a big investment, so buying a car can be a little stressful, but these guys make it comfortable and easy. <time>1496769139925< /time>< Review>
After visiting Audi, Mercedes, and Infiniti, and being let down by their outrageous monthly lease payments for their entry-level vehicles, I came here on a whim hoping to get a great deal on a mid-size SUV or crossover. I was not let down! This was my first time leasing a car, and I was bit hesitant and nervous when I walked in the door, but Mack made me feel at ease with the entire process. I have purchased 3 cars in my life, and never have I felt more comfortable with a sales person than I did with Mack. He was kind, humble, and worked with me to get my monthly payments to fit within my budget. And even better, he and didn't pressure me while negotiating my payments. He was cool as a cucumber while I asked to look at multiple vehicles and package options (in 90+ degree heat might I add!). I was torn between the X5 and X6, but after test-driving the X5, I knew she was the one. I told Mack I needed a day to think about things, and he had no problem with it. He even encouraged it. The next day I came back, and told him where I needed the payments to be and he was more than accommodating to my needs (I wanted 12,000 miles/year, and BMW is big on pushing the 10,000 miles/year package.) We agreed on a price that beat the competition (and I got my 12,000 miles!). After signing the papers, I couldn't believe how smooth the process went. The financing add-ons they try to sell you after signing are a little obnoxious and intimidating, but I get it - it's how they make $$ on leases. Needless to say, I'm very happy with my new car and cannot say enough great things about Mack. If you're looking for a new car - whether you're buying or leasing - and don't want a young, pushy salesman who's just looking to score a big commission off you, get in touch with Mack. He'll make you feel at ease and will take all the time you need to get you to a price point you're happy with. I never thought I'd be driving a brand new BMW, but Mack made that possible!<//Review>

< Text>
Interestingly enough, I was speaking to a coworker yesterday, who also owns a BMW, and asked him where he had his service done. He mentioned Valencia BMW, we both gave each other that acknowledging frown and proceeded to rant about how poor this dealership is in regards to it's service department. I'm sorry, I wish I had better things to say, but the Valencia BMW service and parts departments have a lot of work to do to even come close to the customer service I commonly experience at Honda, Fiat, VW or even Ford.

Based on my past visits to your service department, I find the Valencia BMW staff indifferent and inattentive, everyone seems like they're just going through the motions. During my most recent visit, while waiting to drop off my car, someone came in who appeared to have worked at this location before and the friendly attention he received was more in line of what your paying customers should receive.

And the wait times, dropping off or picking up, are far too long, even when you have a scheduled appointment. This isn't the first time I've had to wait this long, it happens every time. During my most recent service appointment, I had a 5:40pm scheduled drop-off, I arrived and checked-in early and still wasn't seen by the service advisor until almost 6:10pm.

Then when I came to pick up the car the next day, the porter took almost 30 minutes to bring my car up to the front, even though the waiting room seemed virtually empty. To further my frustration, the porter also left some nice, greasy black streaks on my beige floor mats! Do you folks use any of the paper floor covers that other car dealerships use to protect their customer's interiors?

Adding to this wonderful experience, I walked into the parts departments and a bell rang to alert the staff that there was someone up front waiting to purchase some genuine BMW parts. I stood in a completely empty room for over 10 minutes. I finally went back to the entrance door, opened and closed several times get the door bell to ring a few times before someone finally came out to help me.

Last but not least, is it that difficult for BMW Valencia to set up a system where I can pay for and pick up my parts in the parts department instead of being made to walk back to the indifferent staff at the service desk, pay for my item there, then have to walk back to the parts department to pick up the part? Honda, VW, Fiat and Ford parts departments allow me to pay for and pick up my parts at the same desk. You guys might want to check out your competition. It makes for a much better customer experience.< /Text>

< Review>
It wasn't the best or the worst experience. It was a long distance deal- I bought the car sight un-seen and worked the deal virtually. I had never done that before and I fully expected it would be different, but figured the dealership would work to help me understand the process. They did, but it was challenging. I never felt like my salesman had any interest in the deal, or making it work for me,  or had any enthusiasm for helping me understand the long distance process - he just kept saying "it'll take a while." - Which is fine, I just felt that he could have/should have proactively given me an idea of what it would take, what he would do, and what to expect - which is good customer service. Instead, I just asked a ton of questions and felt they were met with short answers that weren't overly helpful. It was just a lack of explanation in general with the deal that was frustrating. Autonation, offers a 3 day 250-mile warranty that was voided on my deal - likely (I can only assume) because it was a long distance deal. Again, that's not a problem, I had no intentions of returning, but that's an important issue that probably should have been explained. The finance guy was totally rude, I left him a message declining his added products and never got a call back to confirm that the paperwork was on the way - which I think is just rude. There was some issue with the temporary permits - admittedly, I'm not totally clear on what happened, but the optics of it appeared that my salesman dropped the ball and then tried to blame it on someone else when I was frustrated because I couldn't drive the car. Again, it may have just been optics but it felt off. Ultimately, the deal got done, I got the car, and nothing went catastrophically wrong - it was just a general lack of interest by the salesman, I found it odd that he never picked up the phone and called me and last, but not least, that he never bothered to thank me for my business. I know it was long distance and we never met, but I still had a choice of where to go and I chose here - so some appreciation by way of a simple "thank you for doing business with us" - doesn't seem to be an unreasonable ask. In the end I have a great car and I'm glad about that. Like I said, it wasn't worst, but it was far from the best (which is somewhat expected from a BMW dealer).<//Review>

<Name>Crispin Asuncion</Name>< review>
I went in to purchase a used Lexus RX350 for my daughter.  I was assured that this used vehicle went through a comprehensive 150 point inspection.  My wife encouraged me to buy our used car from a "reputable" dealer convincing me that they would not cheat us, but instead be safer to buy a used car from them then from a small dealer or private party.  WRONG!!!

I took in the used Lexus we purchased from Valencia BMW (the car that was supposed to be inspected by professionals at Valencia BMW) into my local Lexus dealership the next day for routine maintenance, and to my shock given estimates for over $4000 in critical repairs!!!

I should have known when the first thing they listed was new battery because the battery cover to the resoivoir on top was missing.  Obviously, they can't get a cover to match, but you would think that when VBMW listed that they checked the battery, they would have listed this obvious missing piece....or maybe they did not check the battery at all.  Anyway, Lexus service department says I have: leaking transmission O-ring, torn control arm bushings, leaking steering rack which means complete rack replacement and alignment, leaking front light housing.

Should any of these been caught at inspection????? Maybe??? Maybe not???

The point is that when I called the next day to explain the situation to my salesman Willie, he essentially says sorry, the car is sold AS IS!  Nothing he can do and that I should complain to the used car manager.  He did not even offer to talk to the manager on by behalf....just sorry nothing we can do, out of luck, the car is as is.  Don't remind me that it is as is...I f&$@ing know that!!!  I get it...you got your money.

Now I completely understand as is, and I have bought dozens of used cars in the past.  My issue is that Valencia BMW says they do a "comprehensive" 150 point inspection to make sure that used cars are worthy to be sold on their lot, BUT I certainly feel like that the inspection was done poorly, because someone should have caught some of these obvious repair issues...Lexus did!

I don't know cars, but I trust that when Valencia BMW "says" that they checked it, I believe them.

My mistake!

At the end of the day, Valencia BMW DID NOTHING to try to make things right with me, not even a follow-up call after I communicated my issue to Willie my salesman.  It's all on them now.

Decide for yourself if that is who you want to do business with....<//review>

Hilda Torres<//user_name>
<Text>This past Saturday (04/28/2018), we stopped by Valencia BMW to look at a used Suburban.  We took it for a test drive, and told the sales guy we still had a couple of more vehicles to check out before we made a decision.  My husband called Sathy, our sales guy that same night (Saturday) and made an offer on the vehicle.  He said he would call us back in the morning after speaking with his manager.  We waited around for the call on Sunday morning and finally decided to just drive up there as we intended to buy the vehicle anyways.  Our sales guy from the previous day was there and we spoke to him for a bit before his sales manager, Ryan Annett came out.  Now, we were just trying to get the best price we could on this used vehicle but apparently, Autonation does not negotiate with their pricing.  The sales manager made sure to keep pointing this out and said that‚Äôs the way it is and there is nothing they can do about it.  Only corporate could change it.  He had all but a couple of minutes for us and then just walked away.  We told our sales guy we would discuss this privately for a few minutes (in the car) about it and would let him know.  Five minutes later, we decide to buy the vehicle and went inside to look for Sathy.  We sat in their lobby for about 5 minutes before Sathy finally showed up.  We told him we wanted the vehicle and asked if it could be detailed.  He left to speak with his sales manager for what seemed like 10 minutes.  When he finally came back, he brought his sales manager with him, Ryan.  Ryan then proceeds to tell us that they cannot sell us the vehicle anymore because someone reserved it online.  He said that person would be coming in at 7pm that night and we would have to wait till after to hear back from them if it was sold or not.  Then we were just sent on our way.  We were there on Saturday to look at the vehicle, returned on Sunday to buy the vehicle, and now Ryan tells us that they have to give an opportunity to the person who placed it on hold to look at the vehicle?!  We are in disbelief.  We are standing inside the showroom, ready to buy the vehicle but now we cannot because someone has reserved it.  Ryan says there is nothing they can do but they would call us in the evening if the vehicle does not sell.  I could not believe they turned us away because they had someone else who was interested in the vehicle.  I‚Äôm sure they would not have done this to us if were buying a 60k BMW.  I have never been so insulted or embarrassed in my life.  We had cash on hand, ready to buy the vehicle but Ryan used the excuse that someone else reserved the vehicle while we were there so now we cannot buy it.  We never received a call later that evening or even Monday morning to let us know if it sold or not.  A courtesy phone call would have been nice.  It is Tuesday morning and we are still waiting to hear back.  Talk about lousy customer service.  Before all this went down, I should mention what I observed between their staff.  While my husband and I were outside discussing the vehicle, a sales girl walked out of the office.  She began to speak to another employee (male) as he was walking towards her and he flat out passed right by her and ignored her.  He continued on his way towards the office and she turned back and asked him if he was going to help her of if she should ask anyone else.  Again, he ignored her and went into the office.  She soon followed him in and was walking behind him talking to him and he did not acknowledge her.  What kind of business are you running Mr. Coia?  Your employees seem hostile towards each other.  That explains why your sales manager had no time to waste on us.  No respect for each other or customers who are not buying high end vehicles.< /Text>< resp>

Oh my gosh where to begin. Well we just purchased a CPO X5 2 weeks ago. Our salesperson Madison was excellent. She is a very lovely young lady and was very pleasant to work with. The finance guy on the other hand was not so great so after 5 hours after sitting at the  dealership feeling like our heads were going to explode we finally got to leave with our 2013 X5. When we got to run the car on the freeway i knew that something was off on the alignment. I checked our paperwork and on their CPO checklist it stated that it was good but I took it to our local BMW dealership 2 days after purchase. They checked the alignment and it failed and so we ended up paying $265 to get it done. We contacted the sales manager at Valencia BMW and he said he would reimburse us for the cost. I thought wow thats nice but we still haven't seen anything so I'm not banking on it.

Then today i finally took the car in to get it washed (put it off due to the recent rain) and noticed that the passager side back door had scratches on the door. They took a closer look and told me the car had bondo on it and a poor paint job. From there I went to a local autobody shop to get a more accurate opinion and they confirmed that the bondo is starting to crack and would need to repair and repaint it approximately $800 to $1000.

So long story short I'm extremly disappointed. I know that we purchased a used car and I don't expect perfection however when I think of BMW CPO I think quality and that wasn't what we got. The people at Valencia BMW are very nice (with maybe the exception of the finance guy) but I do feel bamboozled. I would say if you go there please just really examine the vehicle, take your time and look at everything so that you don't end up regretting your purchase.</text>

< text>
I live in Los Angeles, and the ride out to Valencia BMW was well worth it.  No one in my research could touch their offers nor had as wide a selection of cars with various options as Valencia.

My research consisted of emailing and messaging every BMW and Audi dealership around Los Angeles. Messaging all the way down to Long Beach and as far east as Riverside.  I wanted to find the best deal on a 2017/2018 BMW 330e lease or a 2017/2018 Audi E-Tron with the options to fit my budget.

Yliana Fetterolf at Valencia was extremely professional, informative and patient throughout the entire finding/negotiating/buying experience.  She would consistently get back to me in a timely fashion (either email or phone) and show me different cars within my budget.  She was never pushy and made me feel confident that Valencia BMW was the place I'd be buying my car from.  I can't recommend her enough to anyone looking at buying or leasing a BMW.

I couldn't be more happy with the deal Valencia gave me on a 2018, 330e lease, no other dealership could come close. Yliana was completely awesome and made me feel comfortable the entire way.  Not only did she do everything in her power to find me the right 330e to fit within my budget but she also drove the car to me.

If you have a BMW in mind, chances are Valencia has it.  Every other dealership I called only had a few cars on their lot in my parameters or colors, whereas Yliana was able to search multiple other places until she found the car I wanted with the options and color I wanted.

Thank you Yliana and Valencia for the awesome buying experience. I highly recommend them and I'll be telling my family and friends to take the trip to Valencia for their next BMW as well!<//text>

< review>
I leased a 2013 X5 from this place. On the test drive of the X5 the car died and we had to be picked up(not out of gas). My wife really wanted an X5 so we decided to go ahead and get a different X5. The buying portion was pretty good.

When it comes to service....STAY AWAY. I've had on multiple occasions times where the service folks would not call back or give you updates on your car. I would come in early as possible(7am) for the regular oil change and I would not get the car until 4-5 in the evening JUST FOR AN OIL CHANGE. One time they surprisingly called me and told me my car was ready and was being washed. So I got dropped off at the service department only to wait for an hour and 20 min, after being told multiple times that my car was being washed. At this point it was taking so long I thought I was getting a detail LOL. When the car finally came out I was just going to hop in and leave, but something told me to do a walk around and boom this is when I saw a big yellow mark/scratch on the front corner bumper. I asked the person that brought the car up and he said "Oh it came in like that" which is a lie because the service adviser does a walk around with the customer(me) when you drop the car off and it was not there, I would have noticed. I told the service adviser and he had no words. They took it back and said they would fix it which they did. Then I started wondering how that would happen and what yellow car did they hit?? Then I noticed that the car wash has 2 yellow poles right in front of it......Lightbulb goes on, the poor pole has been hit so many times, you can see all the markings and paint scraped on it from the service guys hitting it with peoples cars. They had the nerve to blame me saying I brought it in like that.

I was warned by multiple friends that live in the area to avoid this place but i'm stubborn I guess.

A couple of weeks ago my wife and I went to inquire about buying out our lease, but we were told that we couldn't do to a big recall, OK fair enough, but we didn't want to get another car from there. We were hassled by the sales shark\guy to look at a new model which we said no thank you, then he proceeded to ask us to stay for hot dogs and drinks to which we politely declined and started walking away, when we were almost to our car he said well we have "Fried Chicken and Watermelon if you want!!". At the time I didn't think anything of it until I was down the street already, my wife said "did he just offer us Fried Chicken and watermelon?" I said yes he did. I was so close to turning around and going back to see if they actually had it so I could call his bluff. Being African American I was insulted at the petty attempt of a stereotype joke that it was best for him that I did not turn around. Instead they can take this car back and be done with me forever. Never again will I drop another dime here after I return this vehicle. BMW Valencia you should be ashamed.</review>

<review>I bought a vehicle here at the beginning of November 2013. To keep things short and sweet I had nothing but a horrible time since the night I walked in there and made the purchase. First, always make sure you have acquired financing before leaving with the vehicle. I asked the salesman while my friend was with me multiple times about this and my concern with taking the car near closing on a Saturday evening. I was assured there were no issues after the credit check and within 3 days I was asked to pony up more cash for the deal to go through.  In the end it worked out, but please do not make my mistake. Verify with BMW Financial before you even get the seat and mirrors where you want them.

The night I purchased the car I also noticed some marks on the rear of the seats, bright red multiple locations. Since it has an Ivory interior it is definitely noticeable and the salesman asked if it would be possible to contact him during the week and setup an appointment to have this taken care of. I agreed since it was already closing time and believed him that this would be taken care of. A month has passed and nothing. No email response no phone calls returned.  This was also the theme when I was initially asked to put more down for the financing to work....no email response no phone calls returned until finally a resolution later in the week when I was contacted by the Finance Director. So if you could imagine selling your other vehicle the day after the purchase, only to find out there is a problem with financing....then no communication for days on where everything stands. I was a little on edge.

Last thing is when I received my plates from the DMV and prompted me to write this review. I went to install them and the front and rear nut plates were stripped down to nothing because the person that installed the dealer plates had used machine screws to hold everything in place. Front license plate holder was only being held in by one machine screw and another one just long enough to keep the entire bracket in place. What if this was your wife's brand new car and she had the kids with her driving down our already terrible So Cal roads, only to have a tire blow out by 3 inch long machine screws from a front license plate bracket that could not be held in place on your MSRP 63,000 vehicle.

Contacted BMW North America, though sympathetic even after sending pics, still nothing regarding a resolution. I will end up just paying an upholstery expert to help get the marks out. Found a way to rig the plates in place, "rig - To make or construct in haste or in a makeshift manner".

Also no email from either the dealer or BMW on my experience. I have heard this is a regular feedback requested from buyers by both parties.

Be cautious, I know a salesman will promise you the world to get you off the lot in one of their cars regardless of manufacture, but I did not expect this for my first and probably last BMW purchase.< /review><pictures>None<//pictures><response>None< /response><gmapID>0x80c2876cc819b821:0xc72f3c4b40234881</gmapID></record></dataset><record>

Had my 2007 328i towed into Valencia BMW for work. They had to replace the computer and the fuel pump needed a part because it kept popping off. After replacing the parts, they wrote on the invoice, "Car runs flawless" I drove 2 miles and the dang car cut off! Had to return it back to BMW. The next day they said it was a vacuum hose that was loose and they had to fix it. So my wife and I went to pick up our vehicle. Needless to say, we got on the freeway and it wouldn't go past 60 mph. We got right off and headed back to Valencia BMW. As we were stopped at the light, the car didn't do anything but shake like it was having a seizure. So now they say it was the Disa valve. So I had them replace it and the oil pan gasket. After a week, we pick up our vehicle and drive. As we get to the gas station, it wouldn't pump over half a tank of fuel before clicking off. I tried another gas station and the same thing happened. Not only can I NOT fill my tank with fuel, but the engine oil maintenance light comes on and it's showing that I need an oil change. It's also pausing as if it wants to cut off.

So I took it to Vic's Bimmer in Lancaster, CA to take a look at it. I told them what happened and they said they get a lot of complaints about Valencia BMW. They took the fuel pump off to check it and found the the vent hose was NOT connected. They connected it and ran a test. The test showed the DMTL pump was no good. So having them replace the pump, they found that the activated charcoal filter was full of fuel, so that had to be replaced too. So thanks for not correctly hooking my fuel pump back up, it caused these other parts to fail.

And here is the kicker!!! WHY would ANYBODY repairing my vehicle have a reason to go in the arm rest and look around? Not only did they go in my armrest, but they STOLE my damn iPod Classic with all my music on it. Major problem because Apple doesn't make that iPod anymore! So they wanted me to buy a new iPod and give them a receipt to refund me, but OH!!! They have to send it to Corporate to mail me a check that I still haven't received! I will NEVER take my vehicle to Valencia BMW again!! I don't even rate them as ONE star, but ZERO stars!!!!</review>

<Text>Reading these reviews is confusing to me. I've bought two BMWs from Valencia - one a certified pre-owned, and the other a new X5. In both cases I was struck by the high level of professionalism of the sales staff, as well as of the support executives, from Finance (fantastic) to service (knowledgable and fair). My first purchase was with Brandon, who has since been bumped up to finance, but he took care of me like a friend. My second purchase with with "Jim" Hiten Advani, probably the most cultured and knowledgeable luxury car salesman I've met anywhere (turns out he sold luxury cars to oil millionaires in Kuwait before settling in Cali. Then, the most dreaded part of the typical buying experience is the time spent in Finance. A great guy name Mickey Williams took the extra time to understand my personal finances, which were a little complicated due to self employment, and he saved me a point on the great BMW interest rate by pointing out what I'd done wrong in filling out my financing forms. So I hope this doesn't sound too good to be true, but I left Valencia BMW amazed by the quality of the staff they'd assembled there, and by the real sense of comraderie that I felt during the car selection and buying process. I give this dealership and its folks five big stars!< /Text><GmapID>0x80c2876cc819b821:0xc72f3c4b40234881</GmapID><user>105774655366561717493</user>< pics>

<Time>1402610627156< /Time>< Review>
I have been shopping for a new "fun" car for some time and ran thru the whole gamut of sport / luxury sedans.  After driving various cars, and a number of BMW models, I decided that I wanted a new or very low mile 550i.

I had previously visited Valencia BMW in the past 6 months when casually looking at several other cars, and both of my previous visits had been pleasant and stress free.  So, after shopping and driving a couple local dealers near my home in Ventura, I went out to visit Valencia BMW.

The salesman I worked with, Robert Grass, a longtime BMW enthusiast, was professional, upbeat and very knowledgeable.  He found a perfect used 2014 550i for me with very low miles, gave an excellent overview of the car and after taking a drive, we worked out our deal.  They were very efficient and having shopped around considerably, they were both easy to deal with and competitively priced. I could not have been happier with the car and after filling out a credit application and various paperwork, was quickly moved into their Finance office.

The Finance director, Amir Mansour, was a pleasure to work with as well.  He was fast with all of the DMV paperwork and it was easy to see why he had been with the company for 15 years as he was very good at his job. On the way out, I was introduced to Mr. Gary Pilikyan, the General Manager.  He was a very nice man and I complimented him on how well run and professional his store was.

After I had taken delivery of the car, another gentleman spent about 25 minutes teaching me about all the technology (I am a first time BMW owner) and making sure I was comfortable with leaving in my new vehicle.  And finally, they confirmed my home address so that they could have my SUV dropped off at my house the next day, which eliminated me having to drive back with someone to get it.

In summary, I was floored by the professionalism and courtesy I experienced from Valencia BMW.  I do not casually give out glowing recommendations so I can promise you this, they absolutely earned all of the accolades I'm giving them.

And needless to say, I plan to come back and buy more cars from them in the future..< /Review>
